00:07:34.454 --> 00:07:38.583
converging forces that can result in three different outcomes,

00:07:38.583 --> 00:07:41.919
two of those outcomes being catastrophic in the three forces

00:07:41.919 --> 00:07:45.631
that are converging or threats to civilization in society.

00:07:45.631 --> 00:07:49.177
So the three threats or what he calls generator functions,

00:07:49.385 --> 00:07:52.555
or first rivalrous dynamics, which are win

00:07:52.555 --> 00:07:56.309
lose games where one party's gain requires another's loss.

00:07:56.434 --> 00:08:00.188
So think arms races or corporate competition, or social media

00:08:00.188 --> 00:08:04.233
content and academic publishing
like hoarding data to publish first.

00:08:04.275 --> 00:08:06.360
The second is substrate consumption.

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:09.614
Substrate is what something needs to exist, like soil

00:08:09.614 --> 00:08:12.992
for plants, attention for media, or trust for markets.

00:08:12.992 --> 00:08:17.788
When systems consume their foundation faster
than they can regenerate, that's bad.

00:08:17.830 --> 00:08:22.126
So you can think depleting topsoil
that took millennia to form and the attention

00:08:22.126 --> 00:08:26.506
economy consuming human cognitive capacity
faster than it recovers.

00:08:26.506 --> 00:08:29.133
And the third threat is exponential technology.

00:08:29.133 --> 00:08:33.930
So tools and systems that improve themselves
at accelerating rates, outpacing human wisdom.

00:08:34.096 --> 00:08:38.184
You can think AI doubling in capacity,
automated weapons and social media

00:08:38.184 --> 00:08:42.438
algorithms evolving faster than we can study
their psychological impacts.

00:08:42.438 --> 00:08:47.568
So when those three things converge,
they can result in civilizational collapse.

00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:53.366
